description.narrative:
The main objective of the intervention is to measure the micronutrient status, micronutrient intakes levels and the effective coverage of current nutrition interventions amongst targeted populations in Zambia.

The specific objectives are to determine the following;
1) Prevalence of micronutrient deficiencies in children 6-59 months of age, adolescent girls 11-19 years of age, Women of Reproductive Age (15-49) and men 21-59 years of age at provincial and national levels. 
2) Daily intake of macronutrients (energy, protein, fat and carbohydrates) and critical vitamins and minerals (calcium, iron, zinc, vitamin A, vitamin C and B-vitamins) for children 6-59 months of age, adolescents 11-19 years of age, Women of Reproductive Age (WRA) and men 21-59 years of age at provincial and national levels;
 3) Household and individual coverage of fortified sugar and contribution to total diet intake of vitamin A and iodized salt at provincial and national levels;
 4) Household and individual access to orange-fleshed sweet potato and orange maize and contribution to total diet intake of vitamin A in children 6-59 months of age, adolescent girls 11-19 years of age, Women of Reproductive Age (WRA) and men 21-59 years of age at provincial and national levels;
 5) Individual coverage of the following nutrition interventions implemented at scale at the national and provincial level: 
o   Receipt of vitamin A supplementation services for children 6-59 months of age;
o   Receipt of postnatal vitamin A supplementation for women within 6 weeks of delivery;
o   Receipt and utilization of iron supplementation for pregnant women.
o   Receipt and utilization of multiple micronutrient powders among children 6-23 months of age; 
o   Receipt of deworming tablets  for children 12-59 months of age.
o   Zinc supplementation for the treatment of diarrhea for children 6 – 59 months
6) Prevalence of core Infant Young Child Feeding (IYCF) practices, including the following indicators stratified at the National and/or locaion;
o   Exclusive breastfeeding for infants 0-5 months;
o   Early initiation of breastfeeding (within first hour of birth) among infants 0-5 months;
o   Minimum dietary diversity for children 6-23 months;
o   Minimum meal frequency for children 6-23 months; and
o   Minimum acceptable diet for children 6-23 months.
